WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.824
Cardiogenic pulmonary edema is a
life-threatening condition where fluid floods the alveoli due

2
00:00:04.824 --> 00:00:07.824
to increased hydrostatic pressure from
left-sided heart failure.

3
00:00:08.625 --> 00:00:11.145
For respiratory therapists, this is not
just a lung problem.

4
00:00:11.324 --> 00:00:13.465
It's a cardiac-driven gas exchange
emergency.

5
00:00:13.984 --> 00:00:16.924
When the left ventricle fails to pump
effectively, blood backs

6
00:00:16.924 --> 00:00:18.385
up into the pulmonary circulation.

7
00:00:19.084 --> 00:00:22.465
This increases capillary pressure, forcing
fluid out into the interstitial

8
00:00:22.465 --> 00:00:26.184
space and eventually into the alveoli,
impairing oxygen diffusion.

9
00:00:26.905 --> 00:00:28.864
Clinically, patients present with acute
dyspnea,

10
00:00:28.864 --> 00:00:31.325
orthopnea, tachypnea, and often pink,

11
00:00:31.625 --> 00:00:32.104
frothy sputum.

12
00:00:32.685 --> 00:00:36.224
You may hear crackles on auscultation and
see signs of increased work of breathing,

13
00:00:36.325 --> 00:00:37.724
such as accessory muscle use.

14
00:00:38.264 --> 00:00:41.805
Oxygen saturation is typically low, and
ABGs often show hypoxemia

15
00:00:41.805 --> 00:00:46.284
with possible respiratory alkalosis early,
progressing to respiratory acidosis if

16
00:00:46.284 --> 00:00:47.084
fatigue develops.

17
00:00:47.224 --> 00:00:50.744
From a diagnostic standpoint, chest X-ray
may reveal bilateral

18
00:00:50.744 --> 00:00:53.485
infiltrates, often described as a batwing
pattern.

19
00:00:54.084 --> 00:00:58.005
BNP levels are typically elevated, helping
differentiate cardiogenic from non-

20
00:00:58.005 --> 00:00:59.044
cardiogenic causes.

21
00:00:59.784 --> 00:01:03.705
Hemodynamically, these patients often have
elevated pulmonary capillary wedge pressure.

22
00:01:04.605 --> 00:01:08.504
Management focuses on improving
oxygenation and reducing cardiac preload and afterload.

23
00:01:09.224 --> 00:01:12.605
Oxygen therapy is initiated immediately,
and many patients benefit from

24
00:01:12.605 --> 00:01:17.644
non-invasive ventilation like CPAP or
BiPAP to recruit alveoli and reduce work of

25
00:01:17.644 --> 00:01:17.644
breathing.

26
00:01:18.345 --> 00:01:22.205
Diuretics such as furosemide help remove
excess fluid, while vasodilators

27
00:01:22.205 --> 00:01:26.285
like nitroglycerin reduce preload and
afterload, improving cardiac output.

28
00:01:26.964 --> 00:01:30.184
Red flags include worsening hypoxemia,
altered mental status,

29
00:01:30.644 --> 00:01:33.245
rising PaCO2, and signs of respiratory
fatigue.

30
00:01:33.644 --> 00:01:36.644
These may indicate the need for intubation
and mechanical ventilation.

31
00:01:37.364 --> 00:01:40.864
RT plays a critical role in monitoring
respiratory status, applying

32
00:01:40.864 --> 00:01:44.724
and titrating oxygen and ventilatory
support, and recognizing early signs

33
00:01:44.724 --> 00:01:45.584
of deterioration.

34
00:01:46.165 --> 00:01:50.805
Quick recognition and intervention can
prevent progression to respiratory failure and improve patient outcomes.

